Input, Output and Redirection

Three I/O Types
Redirection

I/O Name         Abbreviation   File Descriptor
Standard Input   stdin           0
Standard Output  stdout          1
Standard Error   stderr          2

File Descriptors  - Are numbers that describe open files

Redirection

> Redirects standard output to a file. Overwrites (truncating) existing contents
>> Redirects standard output to a file. Appends to any existing contents.
< Redirects input from file to a command	

& Used with redirection to signsl that a file descriptor is being used
2>&1 Combine stderr and standard output
2>file Redirects standard error to a file.


The Null Device
>/dev/null Redirect output to nowhere
$ ls here not-here 2> /dev/null here
$ ls here not-here >  /dev/null 2>&1






